{"term":"2005","caseName":"Samson v. California","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/2005/04-9728","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - February 22, 2006","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts2/oral_argument_audio/22792","transcript":[{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll hear argument first this morning in Samson versus California.","start":0,"stop":5.282,"duration":5.28},{"text":"Mr. Long.","start":5.282,"stop":6.309,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court--","start":6.309,"stop":10.241,"duration":3.93},{"text":"The search in this case was not based on individualized suspicion, and no other adequate safeguards limited the police officer's discretion to search Petitioner.","start":10.241,"stop":22.505,"duration":12.26},{"text":"For this reason, the search, which would not be permitted by virtually any other State or by the Federal Government, was unreasonable.","start":22.505,"stop":32.607,"duration":10.1},{"text":"The Court has reaffirmed many times that the fourth amendment does not permit the individual officer in the field to exercise unconstrained discretion to search.","start":32.607,"stop":44.175,"duration":11.57},{"text":"The Court has said that the fourth amendment is primarily directed at the evil... it was primarily directed at the evil of general warrants and writs of assistance, and the evil of general warrants and writs of assistance was that they gave individual officers blanket authority to search where they pleased and placed the liberty of every man in the hands of every petty officer.","start":44.175,"stop":68.452,"duration":24.28}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Long--","start":68.452,"stop":68.912,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Long--","start":68.912,"stop":69.479,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--with respect to liberty, as it... it's not disputed, is it, that your client could have had his parole revoked even though the search was suspicionless?","start":69.479,"stop":85.675,"duration":16.2},{"text":"So, we're talking about the difference between revocation of parole, on the one hand, and a separate criminal offense.","start":85.675,"stop":93.172,"duration":7.5},{"text":"Is that right?","start":93.172,"stop":94.249,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, a parolee has conditional liberty.","start":94.249,"stop":98.115,"duration":3.87},{"text":"But, at the time of this search, Mr. Samson was on parole, there was no suspicion of any wrongdoing--","start":98.115,"stop":106.001,"duration":7.89}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But I thought that evidence seized could be introduced, could be a basis to revoke parole.","start":106.001,"stop":115.588,"duration":9.59}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Oh, well, the Court held, in the Scott case, that the exclusionary rule does not apply at parole revocation hearings.","start":115.588,"stop":124.235,"duration":8.65},{"text":"So, if there is an unreasonable search of a parolee that violates the fourth amendment, the evidence could not be admitted at a criminal trial, but it could be admitted at a parole revocation--","start":124.235,"stop":135.237,"duration":11}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"So, the... what the... the consequence here is whether--","start":135.237,"stop":138.686,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I--","start":138.686,"stop":138.886,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--he will have his parole revoked--","start":138.886,"stop":141.124,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I--","start":141.124,"stop":141.374,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--or he will have a separate criminal offense.","start":141.374,"stop":145.906,"duration":4.53}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I understand your question.","start":145.906,"stop":147.251,"duration":1.34},{"text":"In California, Justice Ginsburg, a nonviolent drug offense, the possession of a small amount of an illegal substance, is not a basis for revocation of parole.","start":147.251,"stop":159.347,"duration":12.1},{"text":"It is not possible to revoke parole in California for this offense.","start":159.347,"stop":163.879,"duration":4.53},{"text":"So, parole revocation would not have been a possibility here.","start":163.879,"stop":167.067,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Justice Ginsburg, I suppose, can pursue her own line of questioning, but let me ask you this, because I... her question suggests this, to me at least.","start":167.067,"stop":175.714,"duration":8.65},{"text":"Suppose the parole officer said,","start":175.714,"stop":178.319,"duration":2.6},{"text":"\"Now, look, I'm going to search you. \"","start":178.319,"stop":180.673,"duration":2.35},{"text":"\"If you don't consent, then I'm going to revoke your parole. \"","start":180.673,"stop":184.873,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this, of course, was a police officer, not a parole officer.","start":184.873,"stop":190.166,"duration":5.29}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"I--","start":190.166,"stop":190.449,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But if--","start":190.449,"stop":190.76,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I... my question was a parole officer, and I'll get to police officer next.","start":190.76,"stop":194.381,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--All right.","start":194.381,"stop":194.714,"duration":0.33},{"text":"I think if a parole officer said,","start":194.714,"stop":197.819,"duration":3.1},{"text":"\"You must consent to this search-- \"","start":197.819,"stop":201.601,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"When you see the--","start":201.601,"stop":202.034,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--\"# this particular search\"--","start":202.034,"stop":202.778,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--person on the street, et cetera, et cetera.","start":202.778,"stop":203.789,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"\"And, if you don't, I'll revoke your. \"","start":203.789,"stop":205.466,"duration":1.68},{"text":"--I mean, the consent is not, in this case, first.","start":205.466,"stop":207.987,"duration":2.52},{"text":"I mean, California has said, the Supreme Court has said, parole, in the parole search condition, is imposed as a matter of law.","start":207.987,"stop":215.042,"duration":7.06},{"text":"Your hypothetical poses a question of, Could there be knowing and voluntary consent to a search if the consequence of refusing is revocation of parole?","start":215.042,"stop":225.55,"duration":10.51},{"text":"I would argue, in that situation, that the consequences of refusal are so dire that, effectively, the parolee would have no real choice but to consent.","start":225.55,"stop":238.324,"duration":12.77},{"text":"So, it would be, in a sense, a coerced consent.","start":238.324,"stop":240.829,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Why are they dire?","start":240.829,"stop":241.923,"duration":1.09},{"text":"I mean, he's just back in the situation he would have been in, did he not comply with the conditions of his parole.","start":241.923,"stop":249.987,"duration":8.06},{"text":"I don't see that that's dire.","start":249.987,"stop":251.497,"duration":1.51},{"text":"He has a choice.","start":251.497,"stop":252.447,"duration":0.95},{"text":"He can stay in prison and--","start":252.447,"stop":254.019,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well--","start":254.019,"stop":254.385,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--and suffer the reduction of privacy there, which is much, much greater than being subjected to... I mean, he... he cannot even go to the toilet in privacy.","start":254.385,"stop":264.772,"duration":10.39},{"text":"Or he can go out on parole, subject to the condition that--","start":264.772,"stop":268.31,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":268.31,"stop":268.476,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--that he--","start":268.476,"stop":269.492,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I mean--","start":269.492,"stop":269.642,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--he can--","start":269.642,"stop":270.57,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I--","start":270.57,"stop":270.686,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--be searched.","start":270.686,"stop":271.414,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I have two answers to that, Justice Scalia.","start":271.414,"stop":274.268,"duration":2.85},{"text":"I mean, first, in California, you finish your prison sentence, and then parole is a separate period that happens.","start":274.268,"stop":281.916,"duration":7.65},{"text":"The California Supreme Court said, in People v. Guzman and other cases, parole is not a part of the sentence--","start":281.916,"stop":288.459,"duration":6.54}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but it's--","start":288.459,"stop":288.803,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--in California.","start":288.803,"stop":288.869,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--but it's also clear from the California statute that it is not a right, that it's a privilege, that you get the privilege of parole in exchange... in exchange for agreeing to the conditions, one of which is that you can be searched.","start":288.869,"stop":303.587,"duration":14.72}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's... in California, every inmate gets parole.","start":303.587,"stop":307.525,"duration":3.94},{"text":"It's a matter of law.","start":307.525,"stop":308.963,"duration":1.44},{"text":"It's not a privilege... in Morrissey against Brewer.","start":308.963,"stop":311.557,"duration":2.59},{"text":"The Court... in other cases, the Court rejected the rights privilege distinction anyway.","start":311.557,"stop":316.516,"duration":4.96}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"California statute says it's a privilege, doesn't it?","start":316.516,"stop":318.537,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, in Section 3067.","start":318.537,"stop":322.987,"duration":4.45}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"It does.","start":322.987,"stop":323.454,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But it is... it is also a... Section 3000 of the California penal code says every prisoner gets parole.","start":323.454,"stop":330.884,"duration":7.43},{"text":"It is imposed on the prisoner as--","start":330.884,"stop":333.406,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Even if the--","start":333.406,"stop":333.489,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--a matter of law.","start":333.489,"stop":333.622,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--prisoner... oh, I thought that he can turn it down, and that some prisoners do, if--","start":333.622,"stop":339.331,"duration":5.71}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well--","start":339.331,"stop":339.448,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--if they decide that they don't want to be subjected to searches.","start":339.448,"stop":344.707,"duration":5.26}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--The California Supreme Court has held, in People v. Reyes, and in other cases cited in our brief, that, in California, parole is not a matter of choice, it is imposed as a matter of law.","start":344.707,"stop":356.721,"duration":12.01}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Is... and you mean people are put out on the street when... kicking and screaming when they say,","start":356.721,"stop":360.669,"duration":3.95},{"text":"\"No, I want to stay in jail. \"","start":360.669,"stop":362.096,"duration":1.43},{"text":"\"I don't want to be-- \"","start":362.096,"stop":364.023,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's--","start":364.023,"stop":364.173,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"\"# searched. \"","start":364.173,"stop":364.701,"duration":0.53},{"text":"\"I would rather stay in jail? \"","start":364.701,"stop":366.045,"duration":1.34},{"text":"And--","start":366.045,"stop":366.428,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":366.428,"stop":366.895,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--they are dragged out--","start":366.895,"stop":368.078,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--That--","start":368.078,"stop":368.239,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--into the street.","start":368.239,"stop":368.822,"duration":0.58},{"text":"Is that what happens?","start":368.822,"stop":369.472,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--That is what the California Supreme Court has said.","start":369.472,"stop":371.899,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I--","start":371.899,"stop":372.049,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And what the statutes say is--","start":372.049,"stop":372.565,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--I don't think so.","start":372.565,"stop":373.809,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--That... the statutes say that parole is a... is a transitional period, and that every inmate should undergo a period of parole.","start":373.809,"stop":382.884,"duration":9.07},{"text":"But coming back to your earlier question, the Court has said that the condition of a parolee is very different from the condition of a prisoner.","start":382.884,"stop":392.56,"duration":9.68},{"text":"The Court said that in Morrissey against Brewer.","start":392.56,"stop":395.148,"duration":2.59},{"text":"And the Court said, in Griffin, as to probationers, that while the fourth amendment rights of probationers... and so, parolees, too, we concede... are reduced, there are... the State can go too far.","start":395.148,"stop":408.338,"duration":13.19},{"text":"And if the State exceeds--","start":408.338,"stop":408.954,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, but--","start":408.954,"stop":409.765,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--the permissible limits, it's a violation.","start":409.765,"stop":410.415,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--their condition is very different, in a broad range of areas.","start":410.415,"stop":413.62,"duration":3.2},{"text":"They... you give up first amendment rights.","start":413.62,"stop":416.402,"duration":2.78},{"text":"For example, it's typical to have a condition of parole that you don't consort with known criminals or gang members.","start":416.402,"stop":423.123,"duration":6.72},{"text":"You... often it says you must refrain from alcohol.","start":423.123,"stop":426.661,"duration":3.54},{"text":"Sometimes they say you can't go near particular places, if they think that's going to tempt you to return to a life of crime.","start":426.661,"stop":433.381,"duration":6.72},{"text":"Those are all first amendment rights that are sacrificed while you're on parole.","start":433.381,"stop":438.323,"duration":4.94},{"text":"Why is this any different?","start":438.323,"stop":440.761,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there are many rights that are sacrificed.","start":440.761,"stop":442.855,"duration":2.09},{"text":"What the Court has said about the fourth amendment rights is, because parolees have conditional liberty, they will have a reduced, but not eliminated, fourth amendment protection--","start":442.855,"stop":452.941,"duration":10.09}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What about a drug... what if you're convicted of a drug offense, you're on parole, and one of the conditions is, every week you have to go in for a drug test?","start":452.941,"stop":460.245,"duration":7.3}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, that--","start":460.245,"stop":462.089,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you--","start":462.089,"stop":462.172,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--that would be--","start":462.172,"stop":462.933,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--do you... is that acceptable?","start":462.933,"stop":463.749,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--That would be different in several respects, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":463.749,"stop":466.287,"duration":2.54},{"text":"First of all, there would not be discretion.","start":466.287,"stop":468.309,"duration":2.02},{"text":"You wouldn't have the individual officer--","start":468.309,"stop":469.986,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But it would be a fourth amendment right that you would be giving up--","start":469.986,"stop":472.924,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":472.924,"stop":473.041,"duration":0.12},{"text":"And--","start":473.041,"stop":473.041,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--that you would otherwise have if you weren't on parole.","start":473.041,"stop":475.301,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--And I want to be clear, we are not... we're arguing there is a broad spectrum of searches that States can undertake of parolees, and I'm, by no means, arguing today that all of them, or even most of them, are unconstitutional.","start":475.301,"stop":488.341,"duration":13.04},{"text":"This is a--","start":488.341,"stop":488.541,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"What would you say about a condition that you must... not a regular drug test... you just have to submit yourself to a drug test whenever a police officer asks you to?","start":488.541,"stop":498.067,"duration":9.53}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, you know, that would be much narrower, because it would simply be a drug test.","start":498.067,"stop":504.037,"duration":5.97},{"text":"I think it would have the problems of... the officer would have complete discretion.","start":504.037,"stop":507.658,"duration":3.62},{"text":"If it were like the California--","start":507.658,"stop":508.486,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but it's... I mean, the point--","start":508.486,"stop":510.413,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think it would valid?","start":510.413,"stop":512.351,"duration":1.94},{"text":"That's what I was asking you.","start":512.351,"stop":513.445,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think, because that's a much narrower test, that that could pass muster if... but I would think there really ought to be some guidance to the officer.","start":513.445,"stop":524.28,"duration":10.83},{"text":"I think our ultimate submission today is--","start":524.28,"stop":527.053,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, so that a--","start":527.053,"stop":527.653,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--this is so--","start":527.653,"stop":527.886,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--so that a burglar could be searched for burglar tools--","start":527.886,"stop":531.407,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":531.407,"stop":532.751,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--but not for drugs?","start":532.751,"stop":534.095,"duration":1.34},{"text":"And the drug addict can be searched for drugs, and not burglar tools?","start":534.095,"stop":536.533,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--If it were... if it were tied to the crime that the parolee has committed, you know, that would give it some limitation.","start":536.533,"stop":543.503,"duration":6.97},{"text":"This is a completely unlimited search, for anything, any crime.","start":543.503,"stop":547.203,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--But Justice Stevens's question highlights the point that you criticize about, the randomness of it is often a critical element.","start":547.203,"stop":554.339,"duration":7.14},{"text":"I suppose it makes much more sense to say you're subject to a random drug test than that you have to come in at a scheduled time, when you... presumably, you could refrain from using drugs prior to the test.","start":554.339,"stop":563.931,"duration":9.59},{"text":"And, to some extent, it's the same, even if you're not talking about a drug test.","start":563.931,"stop":567.713,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in all--","start":567.713,"stop":569.307,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The search is only going to be effective if it's not announced or--","start":569.307,"stop":573.089,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, in--","start":573.089,"stop":573.155,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--scheduled.","start":573.155,"stop":573.455,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--and in this Court's suspicionless search cases, you can have a random test where you draw names at random.","start":573.455,"stop":579.131,"duration":5.68},{"text":"There's some other process that doesn't leave it up to each individual officer to decide who gets the drug test or which car to stop to check the driver's license and registration.","start":579.131,"stop":589.301,"duration":10.17},{"text":"What the Court has consistently held as really at the core of the fourth amendment is this notion of the individual officer in the field has complete discretion to decide,","start":589.301,"stop":600.053,"duration":10.75},{"text":"\"Do I search this person? \"","start":600.053,"stop":601.814,"duration":1.76},{"text":"\"Do I not? \"","start":601.814,"stop":602.514,"duration":0.7},{"text":"\"What's the scope of the search? \"","start":602.514,"stop":603.758,"duration":1.24},{"text":"\"What do-- \"","start":603.758,"stop":604.202,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you relying--","start":604.202,"stop":604.868,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--\"# I search for\"?","start":604.868,"stop":605.018,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--on the difference between... you said \"officer in the field\".","start":605.018,"stop":608.056,"duration":3.04},{"text":"Would this be okay if it had been his parole officer?","start":608.056,"stop":612.005,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think--","start":612.005,"stop":612.932,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"The parole officer was walking along the street, saw this guy, and said, \"I'm going to search you\".","start":612.932,"stop":617.214,"duration":4.28}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think it's a very different set of circumstances if we have a parole officer.","start":617.214,"stop":622.858,"duration":5.64},{"text":"This Court has said, at least twice, in Griffin and in Scott, that a parole officer has a different function.","start":622.858,"stop":630.655,"duration":7.8},{"text":"They are not in an adversarial, or a purely adversarial, relationship.","start":630.655,"stop":635.287,"duration":4.63},{"text":"They often think of the parolee or the probationer as a client.","start":635.287,"stop":639.485,"duration":4.2},{"text":"They're trying to see that the person succeeds.","start":639.485,"stop":642.751,"duration":3.27},{"text":"In some sense, the parole officer fails when the parolee goes back to prison.","start":642.751,"stop":647.966,"duration":5.22},{"text":"The parole... the parole officer can act on their entire knowledge and experience with the client, or the parolee.","start":647.966,"stop":656.114,"duration":8.15},{"text":"So, all of that makes a difference.","start":656.114,"stop":657.952,"duration":1.84},{"text":"And the Court has noted that several times.","start":657.952,"stop":660.13,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"When he's in prison, is there any problem about the prison guards intruding upon his privacy, willy nilly, whenever they choose?","start":660.13,"stop":670.965,"duration":10.84}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The... as I understand the Court's--","start":670.965,"stop":671.715,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, walking--","start":671.715,"stop":672.892,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--holding--","start":672.892,"stop":673.042,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--by his cell, which is always opened, and checking in on him to see what's... what he's doing.","start":673.042,"stop":676.98,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--As I understand the Court's holding in Hudson against Palmer, the fourth amendment does not apply in a prison cell.","start":676.98,"stop":684.294,"duration":7.31},{"text":"And--","start":684.294,"stop":684.527,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"So, he's better off on parole than... well, at least no worse off on parole than he would be when he was in prison.","start":684.527,"stop":693.453,"duration":8.93}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--But, Your Honor, that's not the way this Court has analyzed the fourth amendment issues.","start":693.453,"stop":699.745,"duration":6.29},{"text":"It's a different situation.","start":699.745,"stop":701.172,"duration":1.43},{"text":"It is conditional liberty.","start":701.172,"stop":702.683,"duration":1.51},{"text":"It's the... that sort of active grace theory, or right, privilege, distinction, or greater power includes the lesser, all those arguments have been rejected, in--","start":702.683,"stop":710.58,"duration":7.9}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Are--","start":710.58,"stop":710.88,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Morrissey against Brewer, and Gagnon--","start":710.88,"stop":712.807,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"What--","start":712.807,"stop":712.957,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--against Scarpelli.","start":712.957,"stop":713.651,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--Not--","start":713.651,"stop":713.851,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--what do you make of--","start":713.851,"stop":714.534,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--by me.","start":714.534,"stop":714.995,"duration":0.46},{"text":"No, go ahead.","start":714.995,"stop":715.928,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's--","start":715.928,"stop":717.438,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--I was going to say, What do you make of the pragmatic argument that seems to cut all of your objections?","start":717.438,"stop":723.147,"duration":5.71},{"text":"The pragmatic argument is both in favor of complete discretion and of suspicionless search, that the in terrorem effect of knowing that these searches can occur at any moment, in fact, discourages recidivism.","start":723.147,"stop":742.481,"duration":19.33}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":742.481,"stop":742.714,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"What's your response to that?","start":742.714,"stop":743.564,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I have a pragmatic argument, and then I have an argument just based on the fourth amendment.","start":743.564,"stop":748.09,"duration":4.53},{"text":"Pragmatically, no other State, as far as we can tell, and not the Federal Government, authorizes this kind of search; that is, blanket suspicionless discretionary searches by police officers.","start":748.09,"stop":760.108,"duration":12.02}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Apart from--","start":760.108,"stop":760.358,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So--","start":760.358,"stop":760.474,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--Apart from the lack of popularity of the State's view, do--","start":760.474,"stop":764.973,"duration":4.5}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":764.973,"stop":765.173,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--do we have... do we have any empirical evidence that bears on the in terrorem argument?","start":765.173,"stop":770.766,"duration":5.59}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--The... well, the empirical evidence is that all the other States don't seem to be having a harder time--","start":770.766,"stop":775.475,"duration":4.71}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I--","start":775.475,"stop":775.675,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--with recidivism.","start":775.675,"stop":776.502,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--I realize that.","start":776.502,"stop":776.986,"duration":0.48},{"text":"But, beyond that, do we have any empirical evidence, one way or the other?","start":776.986,"stop":780.685,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the California... I think that's a pretty powerful demonstration, but we do have, beyond that, empirically, California was with all the other States until the People against Reyes decision.","start":780.685,"stop":792.615,"duration":11.93},{"text":"Now they've moved to suspicionless searches.","start":792.615,"stop":794.625,"duration":2.01},{"text":"They seem to have about the same rate of recidivism--","start":794.625,"stop":797.063,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"I take it--","start":797.063,"stop":797.297,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--as they--","start":797.297,"stop":797.58,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--the answer is--","start":797.58,"stop":797.907,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--did before.","start":797.907,"stop":798.124,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--we don't have any empirical evidence, one way or the other, apart from the fact that California stands out in its system.","start":798.124,"stop":804.5,"duration":6.38},{"text":"Is that correct?","start":804.5,"stop":805.31,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I... I'm... think I'm offering you evidence that counts as empirical in my mind, but--","start":805.31,"stop":810.22,"duration":4.91}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I--","start":810.22,"stop":810.553,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--apparently it's not--","start":810.553,"stop":811.186,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--I know it, but I've said, about three times, that I want to get beyond the peculiar position of California to any other empirical evidence that cuts for you or against you.","start":811.186,"stop":821.344,"duration":10.16},{"text":"And I take it there really isn't--","start":821.344,"stop":822.604,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, there... we have a footnote.","start":822.604,"stop":824.132,"duration":1.53},{"text":"There is a brief submitted by a Stanford law professor, and we have at least a footnote in our brief.","start":824.132,"stop":829.159,"duration":5.03},{"text":"There is some social science research that suggests that this more intensive supervision is really not effective, if you look at broad numbers.","start":829.159,"stop":838.4,"duration":9.24},{"text":"I mean, I think you will catch some additional people.","start":838.4,"stop":840.577,"duration":2.18},{"text":"I mean, it happened in this case.","start":840.577,"stop":842.182,"duration":1.61},{"text":"But if you step back and look at the overall effects, it's not... it's not particularly helpful--","start":842.182,"stop":848.308,"duration":6.13}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Why--","start":848.308,"stop":848.474,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well--","start":848.474,"stop":848.658,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--Why, if we're going to catch some additional people, is that not sufficient?","start":848.658,"stop":851.996,"duration":3.34},{"text":"That is, why is it unreasonable, say, not for law professors, but business school professors, management consultants, to say,","start":851.996,"stop":859.143,"duration":7.15},{"text":"\"You have a lot of prisoners in California, hundreds of thousands... I don't know, maybe more than 100,000... and we'll tell the Legislature that they can cut the terms, save money, release them early, but we want to have management checks. \"","start":859.143,"stop":873.667,"duration":14.52},{"text":"\"And the management checks are, you might be searched at any time. \"","start":873.667,"stop":877.383,"duration":3.72},{"text":"\"And we catch a few. \"","start":877.383,"stop":878.543,"duration":1.16},{"text":"\"And that's helpful. \"","start":878.543,"stop":880.221,"duration":1.68},{"text":"Now, if the--","start":880.221,"stop":880.815,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":880.815,"stop":881.031,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--State decides that, what's unreasonable about it?","start":881.031,"stop":883.836,"duration":2.81},{"text":"\"They're\"--","start":883.836,"stop":884.236,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":884.236,"stop":884.419,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"\"# letting the people out earlier than they otherwise would-- \"","start":884.419,"stop":886.191,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Because--","start":886.191,"stop":886.274,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--says the Legislature.","start":886.274,"stop":887.868,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Because, Justice Breyer, it has to be a balancing analysis, and--","start":887.868,"stop":892.483,"duration":4.61}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"And what's on the other side?","start":892.483,"stop":893.327,"duration":0.84},{"text":"The other side--","start":893.327,"stop":893.911,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":893.911,"stop":894.077,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--is, you'd rather not have policemen search you, but your alternative is going to be in jail.","start":894.077,"stop":899.797,"duration":5.72}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I mean, the other side is a search condition that says you have... you could be searched at any time, any place, by any police officer for evidence of any crime, is a breathtakingly broad invasion of privacy.","start":899.797,"stop":914.337,"duration":14.54}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"But, of course, that's how it happens when he's in prison.","start":914.337,"stop":916.425,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but he has come out of prison.","start":916.425,"stop":919.958,"duration":3.53},{"text":"The State has seen fit to release him on parole into society.","start":919.958,"stop":923.562,"duration":3.6},{"text":"He has conditional liberty.","start":923.562,"stop":925.156,"duration":1.59},{"text":"And the Court--","start":925.156,"stop":925.834,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But there is a breathtakingly high probability that he is committing a crime.","start":925.834,"stop":931.876,"duration":6.04},{"text":"The statistics cited in the Government's brief say that in an April 2001 report prepared by the California Criminal Justice Statistics Center, 68 percent of adult parolees are returned to prison... 68 percent; 55 percent, for a parole violation; and 13 percent for the commission of a new felony offense.","start":931.876,"stop":955.486,"duration":23.61},{"text":"I mean, it seems to me a breathtaking statistic like that may call for breathtaking--","start":955.486,"stop":963.8,"duration":8.31}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":963.8,"stop":964.033,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--measures to try to police the matter closely.","start":964.033,"stop":968.593,"duration":4.56}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It is a very serious problem.","start":968.593,"stop":970.703,"duration":2.11},{"text":"We don't want to minimize it.","start":970.703,"stop":972.114,"duration":1.41},{"text":"I mean, it is a fact that many... many parolees... and this is true especially in California... end up being returned for technical violations, like not showing up to meetings with parole officers.","start":972.114,"stop":983.711,"duration":11.6},{"text":"Some of the offenses are not as serious as others.","start":983.711,"stop":986.582,"duration":2.87},{"text":"But it is a very serious problem.","start":986.582,"stop":988.243,"duration":1.66},{"text":"We recognize that.","start":988.243,"stop":989.604,"duration":1.36},{"text":"But what the Court has said is that the gravity of the problem cannot justify any means.","start":989.604,"stop":995.39,"duration":5.79},{"text":"There has to be a balancing of the invasion of privacy against the State's need to undertake this.","start":995.39,"stop":1003.288,"duration":7.9},{"text":"And coming back to my second answer to the question you asked several minutes ago, Justice Scalia, I mean, ultimately this search is a... it's a general warrant.","start":1003.288,"stop":1013.279,"duration":9.99},{"text":"It's a writ of assistance.","start":1013.279,"stop":1014.457,"duration":1.18},{"text":"It's limited to parolees, but if the Court is going to stand by what it has said in Griffin and other cases, that their parolees and probationers have some modicum of fourth amendment rights... reduced, we recognize that... this is... this is the core of what the--","start":1014.457,"stop":1032.445,"duration":17.99}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, the--","start":1032.445,"stop":1032.695,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--framers of--","start":1032.695,"stop":1032.878,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--California--","start":1032.878,"stop":1033.496,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--the fourth amendment prohibited.","start":1033.496,"stop":1033.912,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--The California Supreme Court said that the fourth amendment applied to these searches, but it only protected in a limited way, along the same lines as we said in Griffin.","start":1033.912,"stop":1043.67,"duration":9.76},{"text":"And the standard they applied was, it protected against arbitrary or harassing or capricious searches--","start":1043.67,"stop":1049.646,"duration":5.98}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but--","start":1049.646,"stop":1049.729,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--which seems to go to your argument, which is centered around the unbridled discretion of the officer.","start":1049.729,"stop":1055.605,"duration":5.88},{"text":"And the California Supreme Court is saying it's not unbridled.","start":1055.605,"stop":1059.204,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--That is their answer to my argument, and I want to be very clear about","start":1059.204,"stop":1063.997,"duration":4.79},{"text":"\"arbitrary, capricious, and harassing. \"","start":1063.997,"stop":1065.758,"duration":1.76},{"text":"That's the California Supreme Court's standard.","start":1065.758,"stop":1068.879,"duration":3.12},{"text":"So, of course, they get to define it.","start":1068.879,"stop":1070.89,"duration":2.01},{"text":"And they have not defined it the way this Court perhaps would define \"arbitrary\".","start":1070.89,"stop":1075.332,"duration":4.44},{"text":"It's not arbitrary, capricious, or harassing if it has a permissible law enforcement purpose.","start":1075.332,"stop":1081.458,"duration":6.13},{"text":"So, as long as the officer says,","start":1081.458,"stop":1082.902,"duration":1.44},{"text":"\"Well, I don't have any reason to think there's evidence of any crime here, but that's what I'm looking for. \"","start":1082.902,"stop":1087.846,"duration":4.94},{"text":"\"Perhaps there's evidence of crime-- \"","start":1087.846,"stop":1089.357,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's--","start":1089.357,"stop":1089.357,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--that's enough.","start":1089.357,"stop":1089.407,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--fine.","start":1089.407,"stop":1089.607,"duration":0.2},{"text":"But it turns out he stops the guy every hour of the day, then he has a pretty strong case that this is for harassment, and it's not--","start":1089.607,"stop":1097.421,"duration":7.81}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well--","start":1097.421,"stop":1097.571,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--for the special law enforcement--","start":1097.571,"stop":1101.275,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, and--","start":1101.275,"stop":1101.453,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--need that accompanies releasing parolees.","start":1101.453,"stop":1104.307,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--And I take it the fourth amendment itself would prohibit that sort of thing.","start":1104.307,"stop":1108.174,"duration":3.87},{"text":"But it... you couldn't... you couldn't justify a general warrant by saying,","start":1108.174,"stop":1111.362,"duration":3.19},{"text":"\"Well, yes, the officer can search anybody, without any suspicion, and he can choose. \"","start":1111.362,"stop":1117.832,"duration":6.47},{"text":"But it... you know, the search can't happen too often, or it can't last too long.","start":1117.832,"stop":1121.103,"duration":3.27},{"text":"That would not be... and you... and you... similarly, it would not be an answer to say,","start":1121.103,"stop":1125.318,"duration":4.21},{"text":"\"Well, as long as he's looking for evidence of crime. \"","start":1125.318,"stop":1127.328,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but your point was that this is the core of the fourth amendment, and they're taking away all of the protection and leaving it to the unbridled discretion.","start":1127.328,"stop":1135.659,"duration":8.33},{"text":"And that turns out to be not the case.","start":1135.659,"stop":1137.236,"duration":1.58},{"text":"Under the law that authorizes the procedure, the California Supreme Court interpretation is that the fourth amendment provides protection against harassment or arbitrary and--","start":1137.236,"stop":1147.227,"duration":9.99}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well--","start":1147.227,"stop":1147.294,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--capricious searches.","start":1147.294,"stop":1148.421,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I mean, my argument is that what is left of the fourth amendment under the California approach is not the core.","start":1148.421,"stop":1155.375,"duration":6.95},{"text":"It's the far periphery.","start":1155.375,"stop":1157.053,"duration":1.68},{"text":"There has never been a case... and we were able to find over a hundred, and perhaps over 200; it depends on how you count... of cases where parolees or probationers have said,","start":1157.053,"stop":1167.138,"duration":10.08},{"text":"\"You know, this search was arbitrary or capricious or harassing. \"","start":1167.138,"stop":1170.326,"duration":3.19},{"text":"It is always rejected, for the same reason it was in this case.","start":1170.326,"stop":1174.274,"duration":3.95},{"text":"The Court says, \"Well\"--","start":1174.274,"stop":1174.524,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Then which way do you think that cuts?","start":1174.524,"stop":1176.218,"duration":1.69},{"text":"There's--","start":1176.218,"stop":1176.634,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--It--","start":1176.634,"stop":1176.734,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--never been a case of a harassing search of a parolee.","start":1176.734,"stop":1179.822,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I--","start":1179.822,"stop":1180.039,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, that's what... or 200 cases in the--","start":1180.039,"stop":1182.427,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I--","start":1182.427,"stop":1182.644,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--in--","start":1182.644,"stop":1183.104,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think it cuts in the direction that it is an empty, vacuous standard.","start":1183.104,"stop":1186.292,"duration":3.19},{"text":"It's a standard--","start":1186.292,"stop":1186.558,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Why?","start":1186.558,"stop":1186.892,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--that's always--","start":1186.892,"stop":1187.275,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Why?","start":1187.275,"stop":1187.719,"duration":0.44},{"text":"If it... if it... if it... it doesn't go to the suspicionless character of the search, but it does say it has to be reasonable in time, place, or manner.","start":1187.719,"stop":1198.804,"duration":11.09}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":1198.804,"stop":1200.581,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"And maybe the--","start":1200.581,"stop":1200.798,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1200.798,"stop":1201.742,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--officers are reasonable in time, place--","start":1201.742,"stop":1203.753,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1203.753,"stop":1203.847,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--or manner.","start":1203.847,"stop":1204.397,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And... but it's... it had... there has never been a case in which a court has rejected a parolee search as unreasonable in time, place, or manner.","start":1204.397,"stop":1214.506,"duration":10.11},{"text":"And you could--","start":1214.506,"stop":1214.506,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"How many times has it been challenged--","start":1214.506,"stop":1216.35,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--As--","start":1216.35,"stop":1216.683,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--on the--","start":1216.683,"stop":1216.983,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--we said--","start":1216.983,"stop":1217.294,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--on the--","start":1217.294,"stop":1217.76,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--at... we found over a hundred cases in which it's been challenged in the California courts.","start":1217.76,"stop":1222.57,"duration":4.81},{"text":"And it--","start":1222.57,"stop":1222.986,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well--","start":1222.986,"stop":1223.053,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I mean, if you think about it, if the search is, say, at night, the argument is going to be... well, if we said we'd not...","start":1223.053,"stop":1229.456,"duration":6.4},{"text":"\"never going to search you at night. \"","start":1229.456,"stop":1230.539,"duration":1.08},{"text":"then you would commit crimes at night.","start":1230.539,"stop":1232.81,"duration":2.27},{"text":"We had a very extreme case in our brief about body cavity searches.","start":1232.81,"stop":1237.77,"duration":4.96},{"text":"And they said,","start":1237.77,"stop":1238.136,"duration":0.37},{"text":"\"Well, that... of course, that. \"","start":1238.136,"stop":1239.03,"duration":0.89},{"text":"--you know, the suggestion was,","start":1239.03,"stop":1240.541,"duration":1.51},{"text":"\"Of course, that would be too extreme. \"","start":1240.541,"stop":1241.968,"duration":1.43},{"text":"But you could see an argument if parolees and probationers knew that that was off limits, that... you know, that would become a--","start":1241.968,"stop":1249.7,"duration":7.73}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"You say there was a case in which, without any special reason, they did--","start":1249.7,"stop":1253.471,"duration":3.77}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":1253.471,"stop":1253.748,"duration":0.28},{"text":"Let--","start":1253.748,"stop":1253.848,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--a cavity--","start":1253.848,"stop":1253.948,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":1253.948,"stop":1254.181,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--And that would--","start":1254.181,"stop":1254.181,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me be--","start":1254.181,"stop":1255.147,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--Oh, okay.","start":1255.147,"stop":1255.525,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I am not aware of any actual case.","start":1255.525,"stop":1256.791,"duration":1.27},{"text":"We posited that.","start":1256.791,"stop":1257.707,"duration":0.92},{"text":"We said... you know, because you don't need to know anything about the parolee, except he's on parole, and you can search for evidence of any crime.","start":1257.707,"stop":1266.199,"duration":8.49},{"text":"You don't need any suspicion that... so, you could have somebody, a sort of white collar criminal, or you'd check someone who's written a bad check.","start":1266.199,"stop":1273.852,"duration":7.65},{"text":"And if you say,","start":1273.852,"stop":1274.452,"duration":0.6},{"text":"\"Well, I think perhaps you're involved in drugs. \"","start":1274.452,"stop":1276.54,"duration":2.09},{"text":"\"Maybe you're one of these balloon swallowers. \"","start":1276.54,"stop":1278.384,"duration":1.84},{"text":"--you don't need any actual reason to think that's happening, you can simply say, \"I want to investigate that\".","start":1278.384,"stop":1283.926,"duration":5.54},{"text":"And the way... you have to investigate by X rays or something else quite intrusive.","start":1283.926,"stop":1288.541,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"The California Supreme Court may... might well hold that it's arbitrary to conduct such an extreme search as a body cavity search, or to... I don't know--","start":1288.541,"stop":1302.743,"duration":14.2}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well--","start":1302.743,"stop":1303.259,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--to decide to search the person when he's in the men's room or something.","start":1303.259,"stop":1310.629,"duration":7.37},{"text":"I mean, there are--","start":1310.629,"stop":1310.962,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--But--","start":1310.962,"stop":1311.145,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--there are a lot of limitations that the California court--","start":1311.145,"stop":1314.067,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--They might, and--","start":1314.067,"stop":1314.5,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--could put on it, within the context of harassment or--","start":1314.5,"stop":1319.276,"duration":4.78}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--But our principal submission, Justice Scalia... I mean, if California said,","start":1319.276,"stop":1323.975,"duration":4.7},{"text":"\"We have a terrible problem with crime in California; and, therefore, we're authorizing every police officer to search every person anytime, anywhere, for any crime. \"","start":1323.975,"stop":1332.884,"duration":8.91},{"text":"that would be, I would submit, the clearest sort of fourth amendment violation you could imagine.","start":1332.884,"stop":1338.593,"duration":5.71},{"text":"It would be a general warrant or a writ of assistance.","start":1338.593,"stop":1341.187,"duration":2.59},{"text":"It couldn't possibly be justified by saying,","start":1341.187,"stop":1343.808,"duration":2.62},{"text":"\"Well, if it gets too extreme, if it gets into body cavity searches, we won't allow it. \"","start":1343.808,"stop":1348.667,"duration":4.86},{"text":"We are talking about parolees, yes.","start":1348.667,"stop":1351.689,"duration":3.02},{"text":"Their fourth amendment rights are reduced, yes.","start":1351.689,"stop":1354.127,"duration":2.44},{"text":"We recognize that.","start":1354.127,"stop":1355.137,"duration":1.01},{"text":"But saying that this sort of absolutely unguided discretion--","start":1355.137,"stop":1359.087,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"But the reason--","start":1359.087,"stop":1359.937,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--there's no sort of--","start":1359.937,"stop":1359.937,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--the reason that people, I think, are saying that is because they have a lot of prisoners, they're trying to create a category of people who don't have to stay in prison, where they have no rights.","start":1359.937,"stop":1370.689,"duration":10.75},{"text":"And the real question is, Can California, in trying to create this interim category, reduce the fourth amendment right in the way you describe?","start":1370.689,"stop":1379.087,"duration":8.4}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--They--","start":1379.087,"stop":1379.087,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course they can't do it, but the justification is not that there is something bad about this particular individual or he's in some kind of limbo.","start":1379.087,"stop":1386.823,"duration":7.74},{"text":"The reason is that there's a policy tending towards release, which California has decided they want to introduce this as a condition.","start":1386.823,"stop":1395.054,"duration":8.23},{"text":"Now--","start":1395.054,"stop":1395.715,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":1395.715,"stop":1396.181,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--and so, what... and the question is, What's unreasonable about that?","start":1396.181,"stop":1399.414,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what's unreasonable about it is that it goes so far in the direction of eliminating the fourth amendment rights of people who are not prisoners... they are... they have conditional liberty... that it is simply not consistent with the fourth amendment.","start":1399.414,"stop":1414.032,"duration":14.62},{"text":"And on the empirical side, California is an outlier.","start":1414.032,"stop":1417.386,"duration":3.35},{"text":"All the other States--","start":1417.386,"stop":1418.147,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"May I... may I ask you--","start":1418.147,"stop":1418.897,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--and the Federal Government--","start":1418.897,"stop":1419.13,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--this question?","start":1419.13,"stop":1420.508,"duration":1.38},{"text":"Part of your appeal of your case is, you talk about the corporate offender or tax dodger, something like that.","start":1420.508,"stop":1425.867,"duration":5.36},{"text":"It seems quite unreasonable, I agree with you.","start":1425.867,"stop":1427.805,"duration":1.94},{"text":"But what if you defined the class much more narrowly and limit it to people who have been convicted of violent crimes of a very serious nature and so forth, and said, as to those, they can have the totally suspicionless search?","start":1427.805,"stop":1440.401,"duration":12.6},{"text":"Would that--","start":1440.401,"stop":1440.584,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":1440.584,"stop":1440.817,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--be possible?","start":1440.817,"stop":1441.245,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I... one of the things we wanted to make... I think there are many things that States can do.","start":1441.245,"stop":1445.961,"duration":4.72},{"text":"They could certainly--","start":1445.961,"stop":1446.888,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"But I wonder whether--","start":1446.888,"stop":1447.522,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--there's the possibility of--","start":1447.522,"stop":1447.966,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--whether you think they could do that.","start":1447.966,"stop":1448.932,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--There's the possibility of individual determinations, based on the individual circumstances.","start":1448.932,"stop":1454.592,"duration":5.66},{"text":"If you went--","start":1454.592,"stop":1454.925,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what I'm--","start":1454.925,"stop":1455.808,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--category by--","start":1455.808,"stop":1456.136,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--I want to see if there is a way that the class could be defined narrowly, because I want to ask the other side if they would allow the search for any ex felon, for example.","start":1456.136,"stop":1463.839,"duration":7.7},{"text":"You could write it in a way that seemed obviously too broad.","start":1463.839,"stop":1466.854,"duration":3.02},{"text":"But is--","start":1466.854,"stop":1467.52,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Right.","start":1467.52,"stop":1467.654,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--there a narrower class--","start":1467.654,"stop":1468.614,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well--","start":1468.614,"stop":1468.831,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--that you think would be acceptable?","start":1468.831,"stop":1469.875,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think this could be much narrower.","start":1469.875,"stop":1471.802,"duration":1.93},{"text":"And, in my view, it would become a much closer constitutional question if it were limited to certain crimes where the legislature or the State made a finding that there's a particular need to have--","start":1471.802,"stop":1483.648,"duration":11.85}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Say you were a--","start":1483.648,"stop":1483.898,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--suspicionless--","start":1483.898,"stop":1484.064,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--terrorist, for example.","start":1484.064,"stop":1485.158,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--And--","start":1485.158,"stop":1485.342,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Just limit it to terrorists, convicted terrorists.","start":1485.342,"stop":1488.846,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, perhaps convicted terrorists.","start":1488.846,"stop":1491.023,"duration":2.18},{"text":"You know, that... and it... that's very different from what we have here, because--","start":1491.023,"stop":1494.805,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--What about drug offenders, given the high rate of recidivism?","start":1494.805,"stop":1498.254,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I... you know, we... I think you would have to see the facts of that case, but if they made a finding that,","start":1498.254,"stop":1503.88,"duration":5.63},{"text":"\"Because of the nature of drug offenses, we need suspicionless searches rather than simply reasonable suspicion, and we need police officers, not parole officers. \"","start":1503.88,"stop":1513.122,"duration":9.24},{"text":"--and there could be other regulations.","start":1513.122,"stop":1515.633,"duration":2.51},{"text":"The Federal regulations, we think, are a model, really.","start":1515.633,"stop":1518.915,"duration":3.28},{"text":"They have lots of limitations on--","start":1518.915,"stop":1520.925,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--Mr. Long, is it... is it fair to compare California to other States?","start":1520.925,"stop":1525.057,"duration":4.13},{"text":"The assumption would have to be that other States grant parole as liberally as California does.","start":1525.057,"stop":1533.121,"duration":8.06},{"text":"Maybe California has made the decision,","start":1533.121,"stop":1534.543,"duration":1.42},{"text":"\"We have too many people in prison. \"","start":1534.543,"stop":1536.987,"duration":2.44},{"text":"\"We're going to let a lot of them out, but we're going to keep them on a very tight leash. \"","start":1536.987,"stop":1542.18,"duration":5.19},{"text":"Why shouldn't it be able to do that +/?","start":1542.18,"stop":1544.702,"duration":2.52},{"text":"to have tighter controls, but let out many more people on parole, which is... which is exactly what I think they're doing.","start":1544.702,"stop":1552.266,"duration":7.56}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, and I... I think they can have tighter controls, Your Honor.","start":1552.266,"stop":1555.454,"duration":3.19},{"text":"They can... they can have... they could have... they could make this a special condition of parole--","start":1555.454,"stop":1561.163,"duration":5.71}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But my only--","start":1561.163,"stop":1561.574,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--rather than a general condition--","start":1561.574,"stop":1561.74,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--point is--","start":1561.74,"stop":1562.19,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--of parole.","start":1562.19,"stop":1562.474,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--the fact that other States aren't as tight doesn't prove anything, because other States--","start":1562.474,"stop":1568.294,"duration":5.82}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well--","start":1568.294,"stop":1568.51,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--may not be--","start":1568.51,"stop":1570.054,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":1570.054,"stop":1570.271,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--be trying to do the same thing--","start":1570.271,"stop":1571.565,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--I mean--","start":1571.565,"stop":1571.765,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--to empty their prisons--","start":1571.765,"stop":1572.826,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--This Court has said, generally, that what the Court has found to be reasonable for one State is reasonable for all.","start":1572.826,"stop":1578.368,"duration":5.54},{"text":"And when a practice is not well established... and here, it's far from well established; California's virtually unique... the Court has taken that into account for--","start":1578.368,"stop":1586.833,"duration":8.47}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose you were in a halfway house, and the State says,","start":1586.833,"stop":1591.365,"duration":4.53},{"text":"\"We're creating a status. \"","start":1591.365,"stop":1592.792,"duration":1.43},{"text":"\"One is, you're a prisoner. \"","start":1592.792,"stop":1595.48,"duration":2.69},{"text":"\"Another is, you're a halfway house. \"","start":1595.48,"stop":1597.324,"duration":1.84},{"text":"\"Another is, on your... parole. \"","start":1597.324,"stop":1599.929,"duration":2.61},{"text":"\"But we want to subject you to suspicionless searches at... in all three stages... prison, halfway house, parole. \"","start":1599.929,"stop":1611.692,"duration":11.76},{"text":"Could they do it for the halfway house?","start":1611.692,"stop":1614.38,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, they might... halfway houses, as I understand it, Justice Ginsburg, are largely now a thing of the past.","start":1614.38,"stop":1620.006,"duration":5.63},{"text":"But if the idea is you would actually be in a custody situation at night, perhaps in lockdown, then perhaps Hudson against Palmer would come into play--","start":1620.006,"stop":1629.081,"duration":9.07}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"This person goes--","start":1629.081,"stop":1630.131,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--which--","start":1630.131,"stop":1630.281,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--out to work, comes back at the end of the day, and is checked in.","start":1630.281,"stop":1633.363,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--And so, your hypothetical is, Could there be suspicionless searches by--","start":1633.363,"stop":1638.395,"duration":5.03}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah, while the--","start":1638.395,"stop":1638.655,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--police officers--","start":1638.655,"stop":1639.305,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--while the--","start":1639.305,"stop":1639.605,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--at work?","start":1639.605,"stop":1639.605,"duration":0}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--The person who is in this semi custody state, he's going to work, and, while he's at his workplace, the police officer shows up and says,","start":1639.605,"stop":1650.179,"duration":10.57},{"text":"\"I'm going to pat you down, and then I'm going to-- \"","start":1650.179,"stop":1656.833,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's--","start":1656.833,"stop":1657.016,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"\"# see if you have drugs. \"","start":1657.016,"stop":1659.255,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--It's a... it's a harder case.","start":1659.255,"stop":1661.016,"duration":1.76},{"text":"Again, our bottom line is, there would need to be some limitations on that individual officer's discretion.","start":1661.016,"stop":1666.902,"duration":5.89},{"text":"That's the core of the fourth amendment.","start":1666.902,"stop":1668.93,"duration":2.03},{"text":"If there are no further questions, I'd like to reserve the balance of my time.","start":1668.93,"stop":1672.528,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Thank you, Mr. Long.","start":1672.528,"stop":1673.456,"duration":0.93},{"text":"Mr. Niver, we'll hear now from you.","start":1673.456,"stop":1675.633,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it... may it please the Court--","start":1675.633,"stop":1690.351,"duration":14.72},{"text":"Alarmed by the State rate of recidivism and revocation of the more than 100,000 parolees, California enacted a statute which authorized the search of a parolee based solely on his status as a parolee.","start":1690.351,"stop":1706.546,"duration":16.19},{"text":"We submit that such a search is reasonable under the fourth amendment.","start":1706.546,"stop":1710.078,"duration":3.53},{"text":"As this Court held recently in United States versus Knights, to determine the validity of the search we balance the State's need to search against the privacy interest affected.","start":1710.078,"stop":1721.925,"duration":11.85},{"text":"Here, the need is overwhelming, and the privacy interest is dramatically reduced.","start":1721.925,"stop":1728.068,"duration":6.14},{"text":"Turning first to Petitioner's expectation of privacy, it is greatly diminished.","start":1728.068,"stop":1733.954,"duration":5.89},{"text":"Even if it exists, it is far less than that enjoyed by the average law abiding citizen.","start":1733.954,"stop":1740.064,"duration":6.11},{"text":"No one outside the confines of a prison has a lesser expectation of privacy than a parolee.","start":1740.064,"stop":1747.628,"duration":7.56}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Why is that?","start":1747.628,"stop":1748.805,"duration":1.18},{"text":"Doesn't that kind of beg the question?","start":1748.805,"stop":1750.232,"duration":1.43},{"text":"I mean, if we say he's got the normal fourth amendment rights, his... I mean, the expectation of privacy analysis seems to me to be totally circular.","start":1750.232,"stop":1758.547,"duration":8.32}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what the--","start":1758.547,"stop":1758.947,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You say he doesn't have an expectation of privacy, so it's not protected.","start":1758.947,"stop":1762.163,"duration":3.22},{"text":"Well, if we say he does have a... if we say it is protected, then he does have an expectation of privacy.","start":1762.163,"stop":1767.111,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, this Court spoke to that in Knights and said, unanimously that the... in Knights, it was a probation condition, but I think that it... obviously, the same analysis applies here... that the imposition or acceptance of a... of a search condition by a parolee or a probationer results in the severely diminished expectation of privacy enjoyed by the parolee or probationer.","start":1767.111,"stop":1792.565,"duration":25.45},{"text":"And this Court said that unanimously in Knights.","start":1792.565,"stop":1795.17,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Knights involved a situation where reasonable suspicion was required, so it addressed the problem that Mr. Long has of unbridled discretion.","start":1795.17,"stop":1803.744,"duration":8.57},{"text":"You still had to have an articulable reasonable suspicion with respect to the individual.","start":1803.744,"stop":1808.276,"duration":4.53}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"That is true, Your Honor, but the threshold question was whether he had an expectation of privacy at all, or to the... the extent of that expectation of privacy.","start":1808.276,"stop":1819.446,"duration":11.17},{"text":"And the Court, in Knights, before it discussed the balance, had to identify the factors in the balance.","start":1819.446,"stop":1828.11,"duration":8.66},{"text":"In terms of the probationer's interest in that case, by virtue of the search condition, this Court said that his interest in... his expectation of privacy was severely diminished, and left open--","start":1828.11,"stop":1846.066,"duration":17.96}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Why... and why was his expectation of privacy severely diminished?","start":1846.066,"stop":1851.359,"duration":5.29}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--Because of the parole's... excuse me... the probation search that was imposed upon him by virtue of the--","start":1851.359,"stop":1859.256,"duration":7.9}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Because of the very practice that's being challenged here today, right?","start":1859.256,"stop":1864.982,"duration":5.73}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, yes.","start":1864.982,"stop":1865.559,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Because he saw something... you... he signed something that said, \"You're subject to searches\".","start":1865.559,"stop":1869.097,"duration":3.54},{"text":"Well, that's what is at issue.","start":1869.097,"stop":1870.18,"duration":1.08},{"text":"It seems to me that it's... I guess I've said it before, he's... it's begging the question to say,","start":1870.18,"stop":1875.056,"duration":4.88},{"text":"\"You can do this, because he has a diminished expectation of privacy. \"","start":1875.056,"stop":1879.105,"duration":4.05},{"text":"How far do you push this?","start":1879.105,"stop":1880.599,"duration":1.49},{"text":"Can you have parolees come in and take a lie detector test every week?","start":1880.599,"stop":1885.225,"duration":4.63},{"text":"Do they have... do they have diminished expectation with respect to their fifth amendment rights?","start":1885.225,"stop":1890.174,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"With regard to the fifth amendment rights, if they are not in custody, then... or even if they are... I don't think that that would necessarily... the... any expectation of privacy would preclude the imposition of a lie detector test, no.","start":1890.174,"stop":1907.313,"duration":17.14}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Was that a yes, you can have them--","start":1907.313,"stop":1909.668,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1909.668,"stop":1910.418,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--You can.","start":1910.418,"stop":1911.195,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1911.195,"stop":1911.662,"duration":0.47},{"text":"But in this case, the--","start":1911.662,"stop":1913.45,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Is--","start":1913.45,"stop":1913.733,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What about--","start":1913.733,"stop":1915.044,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--Is--","start":1915.044,"stop":1915.194,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--What about--","start":1915.194,"stop":1915.61,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--Is that right?","start":1915.61,"stop":1916.404,"duration":0.79},{"text":"I mean, even in prison, I... what... I'm not sure you could even do that if they were still in prison.","start":1916.404,"stop":1923.692,"duration":7.29},{"text":"Can you subject people in prison--","start":1923.692,"stop":1925.386,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, of course, that would not be a fourth amendment claim.","start":1925.386,"stop":1929.829,"duration":4.44}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":1929.829,"stop":1930.079,"duration":0.25},{"text":"No, I--","start":1930.079,"stop":1930.212,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"It would be a different--","start":1930.212,"stop":1931.339,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--The Chief Justice was trying to get out of the fourth amendment into the fifth.","start":1931.339,"stop":1935.205,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--That failing... well, in terms of the lack of a precedent from this Court, you know, at this point we can only speculate, but it seems to me that if a person can be required to submit to a drug test by virtue of the status as a parolee or probationer, I don't think that it is an extravagant step to say that they could be required to submit to an--","start":1935.205,"stop":1962.336,"duration":27.13}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you say the same thing if the offense he had committed was tax evasion or price fixing or speeding?","start":1962.336,"stop":1968.972,"duration":6.64},{"text":"Would the... would a person on parole for any one of those offenses have... be subject to the same risk of a suspicionless search?","start":1968.972,"stop":1978.63,"duration":9.66},{"text":"And would it be justified?","start":1978.63,"stop":1980.652,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--Suspicionless search?","start":1980.652,"stop":1982.246,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"Well--","start":1982.246,"stop":1983.062,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"Where we're back to--","start":1983.062,"stop":1983.246,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--applying this statute to--","start":1983.246,"stop":1985.435,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":1985.435,"stop":1986.029,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--a price fixer, tax evader, speeder.","start":1986.029,"stop":1988.123,"duration":2.09},{"text":"Do you think it's justified?","start":1988.123,"stop":1989.8,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"If he's on parole, Your Honor, if he's... look, this applies to parolees in California who have been convicted of felonies, served time in prison, and have been--","start":1989.8,"stop":2001.313,"duration":11.51}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"And if it's to be--","start":2001.313,"stop":2002.246,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--released on parole.","start":2002.246,"stop":2002.329,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--applied to the tax offender and so forth, how about just applying it to all ex felons?","start":2002.329,"stop":2006.772,"duration":4.44},{"text":"Would that be permissible?","start":2006.772,"stop":2008.533,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"On parole, or not on--","start":2008.533,"stop":2009.543,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"No, just the very fact that there's... they're an ex felon.","start":2009.543,"stop":2012.315,"duration":2.77},{"text":"And let the person know, at the time of his discharge from prison, that,","start":2012.315,"stop":2016.43,"duration":4.12},{"text":"\"This is one of the things that the State is going to exact from you as punishment for your crime. \"","start":2016.43,"stop":2021.13,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--If the person is on parole, the answer--","start":2021.13,"stop":2023.584,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I'm saying--","start":2023.584,"stop":2023.917,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--Oh--","start":2023.917,"stop":2024.117,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--he's not on parole.","start":2024.117,"stop":2024.784,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--he's no longer on parole?","start":2024.784,"stop":2025.611,"duration":0.83},{"text":"Than the entire balance changes.","start":2025.611,"stop":2027.866,"duration":2.25},{"text":"The reduction of the expectation of privacy--","start":2027.866,"stop":2030.637,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"But I'm hypothesizing a case in which the law will destroy the expectation of privacy, because it will provide that all ex felons are subject to search.","start":2030.637,"stop":2040.295,"duration":9.66},{"text":"So, they would know, the same as a parolee now knows, he's subject to search.","start":2040.295,"stop":2043.649,"duration":3.35},{"text":"Would that be valid?","start":2043.649,"stop":2044.91,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--My answer to that is, it would not be valid, Your Honor, because a person, having served his time on parole, the State's overwhelming interest in supervision has ended.","start":2044.91,"stop":2056.245,"duration":11.33},{"text":"The State has determined that that person, having successfully completed his period of parole--","start":2056.245,"stop":2061.8,"duration":5.56}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"But... so you don't--","start":2061.8,"stop":2061.983,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Most--","start":2061.983,"stop":2062.15,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--rely on--","start":2062.15,"stop":2062.483,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--Most States--","start":2062.483,"stop":2062.683,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--the fact that--","start":2062.683,"stop":2062.783,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--don't let felons vote.","start":2062.783,"stop":2063.827,"duration":1.04},{"text":"I mean, that's a punishment that they impose after they're out of prison.","start":2063.827,"stop":2067.692,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, but this is not... yes, Your Honor, but this is really not about punishment, this is about supervision.","start":2067.692,"stop":2073.902,"duration":6.21},{"text":"And if a parolee has successfully completed this parole, has been discharged from parole, then the balance--","start":2073.902,"stop":2082.217,"duration":8.32}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--But then we're not relying on the elimination of the expectation of privacy, because, under my hypothetical statute, the ex felon would know he's subject to it.","start":2082.217,"stop":2090.781,"duration":8.56},{"text":"So, it has to be something other than the absence of an expectation of privacy.","start":2090.781,"stop":2094.646,"duration":3.87},{"text":"Is that correct?","start":2094.646,"stop":2095.822,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--Not... a person who is no longer on parole, there is no longer the overwhelming State interest in supervision.","start":2095.822,"stop":2102.878,"duration":7.06},{"text":"The balance changes.","start":2102.878,"stop":2104.222,"duration":1.34},{"text":"Our position would be that that would not be a permissible search.","start":2104.222,"stop":2111.608,"duration":7.39}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"It seems to me that the principal difference, Mr. Niver, is that when he's on parole, it's in lieu of being in jail.","start":2111.608,"stop":2118.328,"duration":6.72},{"text":"If that's not the difference, you don't persuade me.","start":2118.328,"stop":2121.432,"duration":3.1},{"text":"He has voluntarily accepted the parole in exchange for his getting out of jail.","start":2121.432,"stop":2130.424,"duration":8.99},{"text":"And he'd be in worse condition if he were in jail.","start":2130.424,"stop":2132.518,"duration":2.09},{"text":"That's what, seems to me, makes the difference.","start":2132.518,"stop":2136.134,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's... I think that's exactly right, Your Honor.","start":2136.134,"stop":2138.739,"duration":2.61},{"text":"The ex parolee, no longer on parole, is no longer in custody of the... of the California Department of Corrections, there is no longer an overwhelming need to supervise the person, who, having successfully completed parole, is presumptively not the threat to society that he was that he... when he was a parolee.","start":2138.739,"stop":2159.249,"duration":20.51},{"text":"The balance changes, and such a condition... that is to say a suspicionless search of an ex parolee... I think would offend the fourth amendment.","start":2159.249,"stop":2168.058,"duration":8.81}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Niver--","start":2168.058,"stop":2168.458,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"But what do you achieve by this system that you have that you couldn't achieve by a system that more carefully worked out the rules and conditions of a random search?","start":2168.458,"stop":2176.872,"duration":8.41},{"text":"I mean, rules, so that you avoid the totally discretionary element.","start":2176.872,"stop":2184.519,"duration":7.65},{"text":"And if you want to have management consultants, as I was imagining, have 'em.","start":2184.519,"stop":2190.328,"duration":5.81},{"text":"They're not just going to tell you,","start":2190.328,"stop":2192.833,"duration":2.51},{"text":"\"Go and ask anybody to search anytime he wants. \"","start":2192.833,"stop":2195.271,"duration":2.44},{"text":"They'll have a system worked out.","start":2195.271,"stop":2196.698,"duration":1.43},{"text":"So, why not at least require you to think it through that much?","start":2196.698,"stop":2200.998,"duration":4.3},{"text":"And, otherwise, it is unreasonable.","start":2200.998,"stop":2203.503,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we have disputed Petitioner's position that this is a search, although suspicionless, that it is... that discretion is not circumscribed is our position.","start":2203.503,"stop":2218.287,"duration":14.78},{"text":"And it is, because--","start":2218.287,"stop":2219.131,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, are there manuals... are there any... here is the cop on the beat.","start":2219.131,"stop":2222.669,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":2222.669,"stop":2223.413,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"He sees someone that he knows is a parolee.","start":2223.413,"stop":2225.934,"duration":2.52},{"text":"Is there any instruction that he's been given so that his discretion can be guided instead of rudderless?","start":2225.934,"stop":2233.999,"duration":8.06},{"text":"In practice in California, are all--","start":2233.999,"stop":2237.948,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"In... I'm sorry, Your Honor.","start":2237.948,"stop":2239.958,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":2239.958,"stop":2240.158,"duration":0.2},{"text":"What is the practice?","start":2240.158,"stop":2241.719,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"In practice, the... a search... a parole search may not be arbitrary, capricious, or conducted solely for the purpose of harassing--","start":2241.719,"stop":2252.471,"duration":10.75}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm asking you about what instruction, what training, if you know, are officers given?","start":2252.471,"stop":2259.718,"duration":7.25},{"text":"Or are they given no training, just the law that says, \"You can search any parolee\"?","start":2259.718,"stop":2266.423,"duration":6.7}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, they are not told that they may search any parolee, Your Honor.","start":2266.423,"stop":2269.944,"duration":3.52},{"text":"Rather, they are told that the search must be to rehabilitate, reform, or have some other law enforcement purpose.","start":2269.944,"stop":2279.613,"duration":9.67},{"text":"And they--","start":2279.613,"stop":2279.879,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":2279.879,"stop":2280.046,"duration":0.17},{"text":"The officer says,","start":2280.046,"stop":2281.29,"duration":1.24},{"text":"\"I'm searching to see whether the person has any evidence of crime on him. \"","start":2281.29,"stop":2285.405,"duration":4.12},{"text":"For example, whether he has any drugs on him.","start":2285.405,"stop":2287.583,"duration":2.18},{"text":"Law enforcement purpose, supervisory, I suppose.","start":2287.583,"stop":2292.042,"duration":4.46},{"text":"They want to know whether their... whether their parolees are committing offenses.","start":2292.042,"stop":2295.907,"duration":3.87},{"text":"And yet, that reason would apply to everyone virtually all the time.","start":2295.907,"stop":2301.368,"duration":5.46},{"text":"So, it doesn't seem to be a limitation at all.","start":2301.368,"stop":2304.056,"duration":2.69},{"text":"What... am I... am I missing something?","start":2304.056,"stop":2305.9,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--It does apply... it is a limitation.","start":2305.9,"stop":2309.004,"duration":3.1},{"text":"It is not a limitation that would protect the expectation of privacy of a nonparole--","start":2309.004,"stop":2313.869,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, how does the limitation work?","start":2313.869,"stop":2315.724,"duration":1.86},{"text":"The guy is on 1st Street, and an officer says, you know,","start":2315.724,"stop":2319.662,"duration":3.94},{"text":"\"I recognize this person is a parolee, and I have a law enforcement objective. \"","start":2319.662,"stop":2326.643,"duration":6.98},{"text":"\"Is the person committing a crime? \"","start":2326.643,"stop":2329.665,"duration":3.02},{"text":"\"Is the... is the person a recidivist? \"","start":2329.665,"stop":2332.186,"duration":2.52},{"text":"\"Is the person violating parole? \"","start":2332.186,"stop":2334.707,"duration":2.52},{"text":"So, he searches him.","start":2334.707,"stop":2336.051,"duration":1.34},{"text":"The person gets to 2nd Street, another officer does the same thing.","start":2336.051,"stop":2341.677,"duration":5.63},{"text":"Three hours later, a third officer does the same thing.","start":2341.677,"stop":2345.376,"duration":3.7},{"text":"In each case, it seems to me, their justification would not fall afoul of the arbitrary, capricious, or harassment standard.","start":2345.376,"stop":2355.367,"duration":9.99},{"text":"It's not coordinated.","start":2355.367,"stop":2356.561,"duration":1.19},{"text":"They have a... both a parole and a law enforcement objective.","start":2356.561,"stop":2361.328,"duration":4.77},{"text":"Why is there any limitation, then, on the right to search?","start":2361.328,"stop":2365.266,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--If these are, as I understand Your Honor's hypothetical, three independent searches--","start":2365.266,"stop":2370.819,"duration":5.55}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Uh huh.","start":2370.819,"stop":2371.119,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--to the extent that that could happen, and I suppose it could, the... again, the limitation is that it be, as Your Honor states, for a valid law enforcement purpose, and it would require--","start":2371.119,"stop":2388.542,"duration":17.42}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2388.542,"stop":2388.809,"duration":0.27},{"text":"No, but let's get behind the rhetoric.","start":2388.809,"stop":2390.719,"duration":1.91},{"text":"Is there any reason my hypothetical could not, in fact, turn out to be true?","start":2390.719,"stop":2395.845,"duration":5.13}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--There is no--","start":2395.845,"stop":2397.617,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Apart from the unlikelihood of all those police officers out there.","start":2397.617,"stop":2400.471,"duration":2.85},{"text":"But, leaving that aside, is there... is there any reason, in the standard, that my hypothetical could not be true?","start":2400.471,"stop":2406.781,"duration":6.31}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Your Honor, no, there is no reason, but it would... it requires more than testimony by the officers.","start":2406.781,"stop":2413.485,"duration":6.7},{"text":"If the officers at... each testified that they conducted the search, they're... also requires a finding of fact by the trial court that the searches were, in fact, for a valid law enforcement purpose.","start":2413.485,"stop":2426.508,"duration":13.02}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":2426.508,"stop":2426.692,"duration":0.18},{"text":"I mean, let's assume the police are telling the truth, and the judge says, \"Sure\".","start":2426.692,"stop":2429.713,"duration":3.02},{"text":"So, there is no limitation.","start":2429.713,"stop":2431.384,"duration":1.67},{"text":"And it sounds to me, then, as though about the only limitation that would be enforceable would be the limitation against harassment.","start":2431.384,"stop":2440.626,"duration":9.24},{"text":"If one officer did it every 15 minutes to the same person, or if there were a departmental systematic policy saying, you know, \"Get so and so\", that I can understand as being a limitation.","start":2440.626,"stop":2455.15,"duration":14.52},{"text":"But I don't see any other limit.","start":2455.15,"stop":2456.411,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the limitation is, as Your Honor states, if it's a... for a valid law enforcement purpose or to promote rehabilitation or--","start":2456.411,"stop":2465.985,"duration":9.57}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I realize--","start":2465.985,"stop":2466.935,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--recommend--","start":2466.935,"stop":2467.163,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--but do you--","start":2467.163,"stop":2467.563,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--But--","start":2467.563,"stop":2467.846,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--do you agree that there is not any practical limitation, other than the harassment limitation?","start":2467.846,"stop":2472.705,"duration":4.86}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--I... well, that harassment limitation is sufficient to protect the residuum of an expectation--","start":2472.705,"stop":2480.176,"duration":7.47}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, maybe--","start":2480.176,"stop":2480.46,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--of--","start":2480.46,"stop":2480.737,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--maybe it is.","start":2480.737,"stop":2481.22,"duration":0.48},{"text":"But what's the answer to my question?","start":2481.22,"stop":2482.714,"duration":1.49},{"text":"Is that, in practical terms, the only limitation?","start":2482.714,"stop":2485.636,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--It is a... but it... yes, Your Honor, that is the protection.","start":2485.636,"stop":2490.678,"duration":5.04}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":2490.678,"stop":2490.828,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought you said that maybe cavity searches would not... would not be allowed without some special reason for them.","start":2490.828,"stop":2498.409,"duration":7.58},{"text":"And that wouldn't necessarily be harassment.","start":2498.409,"stop":2501.197,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it depends on the circumstances of the search.","start":2501.197,"stop":2505.879,"duration":4.68}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes--","start":2505.879,"stop":2506.029,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"There's an--","start":2506.029,"stop":2507.141,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--I mean--","start":2507.141,"stop":2507.374,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--overarching principle here, under the fourth amendment, that the search be reasonable, in terms of manner and scope.","start":2507.374,"stop":2514.027,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--Okay.","start":2514.027,"stop":2514.288,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"That applies equally to a suspicionless search as it would to a search based on individual suspicion.","start":2514.288,"stop":2520.664,"duration":6.38},{"text":"To that extent, it's really not an issue that arises from the fact that this is suspicionless.","start":2520.664,"stop":2527.645,"duration":6.98}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"What would be arbitrary and capricious?","start":2527.645,"stop":2530.333,"duration":2.69},{"text":"You told us harassing would be the repeated searches by the same officer.","start":2530.333,"stop":2537.803,"duration":7.47}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"Or an--","start":2537.803,"stop":2539.147,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"What--","start":2539.147,"stop":2539.313,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--Or a needlessly intrusive search, as has been just described, or--","start":2539.313,"stop":2544.689,"duration":5.38}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's assume... let's assume that the cavity search is demanded at the bus station, and the officer says,","start":2544.689,"stop":2553.337,"duration":8.65},{"text":"\"We know that drugs get transported by people who ingest them in the balloons, and they get on buses and they travel back and forth from city A to city B.. \"","start":2553.337,"stop":2564.356,"duration":11.02},{"text":"Any reason that that would run afoul of arbitrary and capricious?","start":2564.356,"stop":2570.81,"duration":6.45}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--Depends on the circumstances of the search.","start":2570.81,"stop":2573.581,"duration":2.77},{"text":"Again, Your Honor--","start":2573.581,"stop":2574.258,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"All I'm telling you is, he's at a bus station.","start":2574.258,"stop":2576.269,"duration":2.01},{"text":"The facts are that a lot of people who travel on buses are drug couriers.","start":2576.269,"stop":2582.406,"duration":6.14},{"text":"This person is a parolee.","start":2582.406,"stop":2584.927,"duration":2.52},{"text":"Would that run afoul of the... of any arbitrary and capricious limitation?","start":2584.927,"stop":2589.393,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--It would, for example, if it were done in public view.","start":2589.393,"stop":2593.742,"duration":4.35},{"text":"If the officer didn't, then--","start":2593.742,"stop":2596.097,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, sure, but the officer says,","start":2596.097,"stop":2597.607,"duration":1.51},{"text":"\"All right. \"","start":2597.607,"stop":2598.023,"duration":0.42},{"text":"\"I'm taking you down to the station for a cavity search. \"","start":2598.023,"stop":2602.055,"duration":4.03}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--Again, the office... if the officer did it under those circumstances, it's for the finder of fact to decide whether it was done for a legitimate purpose or--","start":2602.055,"stop":2614.568,"duration":12.51}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you're... I'm asking you to be the finder of fact for me.","start":2614.568,"stop":2617.424,"duration":2.86},{"text":"This is the officer's explanation.","start":2617.424,"stop":2620.212,"duration":2.79},{"text":"This is the factual... set of factual premises on which he acts.","start":2620.212,"stop":2624.904,"duration":4.69},{"text":"Has he violated the arbitrary and capricious limitation?","start":2624.904,"stop":2628.686,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--If, in fact, it was for the purpose that you state, a legitimate law enforcement purpose, and he has been removed from public view, and it's reasonable, in terms of manner and intensity, then it would be permissible.","start":2628.686,"stop":2644.898,"duration":16.21}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"I have one--","start":2644.898,"stop":2645.398,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, suppose you couldn't--","start":2645.398,"stop":2645.581,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--I have one--","start":2645.581,"stop":2646.081,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--you couldn't--","start":2646.081,"stop":2646.414,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--I have--","start":2646.414,"stop":2646.481,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--conduct cavity searches without some special reason, even in prison.","start":2646.481,"stop":2651.957,"duration":5.48},{"text":"Wouldn't that be... isn't there some remnant of a fourth amendment right in prison that you cannot subject, you know, the whole cellblock to cavity searches?","start":2651.957,"stop":2663.554,"duration":11.6}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"That would depend, Your Honor, on the prison, the prison regs, the State.","start":2663.554,"stop":2668.93,"duration":5.38},{"text":"I can't answer that question--","start":2668.93,"stop":2670.357,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I--","start":2670.357,"stop":2670.824,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--in--","start":2670.824,"stop":2671.024,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--I thought the assumption of your answer to my question a moment ago was that there was no such limitation, so far as California is concerned.","start":2671.024,"stop":2678.66,"duration":7.64}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, there is a limitation, in terms of manner and scope.","start":2678.66,"stop":2681.682,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, sure.","start":2681.682,"stop":2682.059,"duration":0.38},{"text":"But we... the manner, in this case, is, they take him down to the station, so that they're not going through this in the middle of a crowded bus terminal.","start":2682.059,"stop":2689.413,"duration":7.35},{"text":"But the point of the question was, any parolee at a bus terminal could be subjected to this demand for search, and I thought your answer was, yes, he could be.","start":2689.413,"stop":2701.693,"duration":12.28},{"text":"And now, in response to Justice Scalia's question, you're saying,","start":2701.693,"stop":2707.563,"duration":5.87},{"text":"\"Well, there may be some limitation. \"","start":2707.563,"stop":2709.157,"duration":1.59},{"text":"So, which is it?","start":2709.157,"stop":2710.834,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"That if the search is a... for a valid law enforcement purpose, and it is reasonable in scope and manner, then it is a permissible parolee search, in California.","start":2710.834,"stop":2722.848,"duration":12.01}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Does it depend... I mean, what if he's on parole for transporting drugs in balloons from bus stations?","start":2722.848,"stop":2728.14,"duration":5.29},{"text":"Does that make a difference +/?","start":2728.14,"stop":2729.318,"duration":1.18},{"text":"as opposed to, he's on parole for tax fraud.","start":2729.318,"stop":2731.672,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"It certainly might, Your Honor.","start":2731.672,"stop":2733.516,"duration":1.84},{"text":"And, again, that would be... that... an additional bit of evidence to present... to be presented to the suppression court to determine whether the scope of the search was reasonable.","start":2733.516,"stop":2746.54,"duration":13.02}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--But all this is on a case... would be on a case by case basis.","start":2746.54,"stop":2749.978,"duration":3.44},{"text":"There are no going in guides for the officer on the street.","start":2749.978,"stop":2754.771,"duration":4.79}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"It's necessarily determined on the... any search has to be decided... the reasonableness of any search has to be decided on a case by case basis.","start":2754.771,"stop":2763.119,"duration":8.35}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Do we--","start":2763.119,"stop":2763.535,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"But the reasonableness here would be unreasonable, unless there are some checks.","start":2763.535,"stop":2768.15,"duration":4.62},{"text":"We're talking about suspicionless searches.","start":2768.15,"stop":2770.338,"duration":2.19},{"text":"And you could have checks.","start":2770.338,"stop":2772.515,"duration":2.18},{"text":"But what about saying... why is it reasonable to do it without any rule based controls on the behavior of the police?","start":2772.515,"stop":2782.091,"duration":9.58},{"text":"That's the question.","start":2782.091,"stop":2783.518,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":2783.518,"stop":2784.279,"duration":0.76},{"text":"And the answer is, in terms of the competing interests, the lowered expectations--","start":2784.279,"stop":2790.832,"duration":6.55}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":2790.832,"stop":2791.032,"duration":0.2},{"text":"But what interest does it serve not to have some rules, manuals, regulations that help make sure it really is random, or help make sure it isn't harassing, or help make sure that it's serving the very ends that you hope to serve with the suspicionless searches?","start":2791.032,"stop":2807.76,"duration":16.73}]},{"speakerName":"Ronald E. Niver","textObjs":[{"text":"--If a State wishes to adopt such rules, those would... may comply with the fourth amendment.","start":2807.76,"stop":2816.158,"duration":8.4},{"text":"The question is not, What could be done?","start":2816.158,"stop":2818.413,"duration":2.26},{"text":"The question is, What was done?","start":2818.413,"stop":2820.007,"duration":1.59},{"text":"The question is whether California's rule, which permits parolee searches that... with the... absolute prohibition of arbitrary, capricious, and harassing suits, and which must be conducted under the fourth amendment, in terms... reasonable, in terms of time, place, manner, and scope... the question is whether that system, the California scheme, is constitutional under the fourth amendment.","start":2820.007,"stop":2845.56,"duration":25.55},{"text":"And here, the system was designed to address an overwhelming problem that the Court, this Court, has well defined.","start":2845.56,"stop":2853.458,"duration":7.9},{"text":"The... over 100,000 parolees are on the street at any given time.","start":2853.458,"stop":2858.484,"duration":5.03},{"text":"Almost 90,000 of them will be revoked in any given period.","start":2858.484,"stop":2864.376,"duration":5.89},{"text":"They... the California parolees require intense supervision.","start":2864.376,"stop":2870.496,"duration":6.12},{"text":"The statute, 3067, was enacted to permit that kind of intense supervision.","start":2870.496,"stop":2878.478,"duration":7.98},{"text":"And the protection afforded to the parolee, in terms of a requirement of a proper purpose--","start":2878.478,"stop":2888.803,"duration":10.32}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Niver.","start":2888.803,"stop":2890.907,"duration":2.1},{"text":"Mr. Marcus.","start":2890.907,"stop":2900.732,"duration":9.82}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":2900.732,"stop":2902.076,"duration":1.34},{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court--","start":2902.076,"stop":2905.359,"duration":3.28},{"text":"Concerned about the threat that parolees pose to public safety, the California Legislature, in 1996, authorized both police and parole officers to search them without individualized suspicion.","start":2905.359,"stop":2916.361,"duration":11},{"text":"Whether evaluated under the special needs doctrine applied in Griffin, or the totality of the circumstances approach applied in Knights, the search of Petitioner in this case, pursuant to his search condition, was reasonable under the fourth amendment.","start":2916.361,"stop":2927.88,"duration":11.52}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Do we have--","start":2927.88,"stop":2928.224,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But not the consent--","start":2928.224,"stop":2928.424,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--to decide--","start":2928.424,"stop":2928.857,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--not the consent approach, I take it.","start":2928.857,"stop":2931.562,"duration":2.7},{"text":"I didn't get an opportunity to ask the counsel who argued just previously.","start":2931.562,"stop":2937.271,"duration":5.71},{"text":"Seemed to me that he argued consent when he answered Justice Stevens's question about the tax evader.","start":2937.271,"stop":2946.18,"duration":8.91},{"text":"But he argued the overwhelming practical needs when he argued the rest of the case.","start":2946.18,"stop":2952.983,"duration":6.8},{"text":"And I thought I saw some tension in the argument there.","start":2952.983,"stop":2957.015,"duration":4.03},{"text":"And I take it the Government does not embrace the consent argument?","start":2957.015,"stop":2959.537,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we do embrace it.","start":2959.537,"stop":2960.797,"duration":1.26},{"text":"We... but we briefed--","start":2960.797,"stop":2962.391,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But you--","start":2962.391,"stop":2962.741,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--the--","start":2962.741,"stop":2962.824,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--just--","start":2962.824,"stop":2963.057,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--It--","start":2963.057,"stop":2963.207,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--put it in number--","start":2963.207,"stop":2963.357,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--We--","start":2963.357,"stop":2963.524,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--you put it--","start":2963.524,"stop":2963.707,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--We--","start":2963.707,"stop":2963.941,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--in number three?","start":2963.941,"stop":2964.535,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--Right.","start":2964.535,"stop":2965.368,"duration":0.83},{"text":"It--","start":2965.368,"stop":2965.501,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"In--","start":2965.501,"stop":2965.585,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--well, primarily... for a couple of reasons.","start":2965.585,"stop":2967.389,"duration":1.8},{"text":"First, Your Honor, the California Supreme Court has not had a chance to interpret 3067(a), you know, after the Reyes decision.","start":2967.389,"stop":2975.787,"duration":8.4},{"text":"They weren't interpreting it there.","start":2975.787,"stop":2976.964,"duration":1.18},{"text":"And so, they haven't had a chance to revisit their ruling that, as a matter of State law, it's not... there's no consent when it comes to a parolee.","start":2976.964,"stop":2983.685,"duration":6.72},{"text":"And that's... so, we thought maybe that would be a reason this Court, prudentially, wouldn't want to reach that issue.","start":2983.685,"stop":2988.217,"duration":4.53},{"text":"And, secondly, the... while the joint appendix contains a portion of the agreement that the Petitioner signed, it doesn't contain the whole content of the agreement.","start":2988.217,"stop":2997.791,"duration":9.57},{"text":"The appellate record doesn't contain the whole content of the agreement.","start":2997.791,"stop":3000.313,"duration":2.52},{"text":"So, we didn't--","start":3000.313,"stop":3001.658,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--But in your view, if the consent was straightforward in the documents, would that be the strongest argument or the weakest argument?","start":3001.658,"stop":3009.555,"duration":7.9}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I think--","start":3009.555,"stop":3010.721,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, I take you'll win on any--","start":3010.721,"stop":3011.732,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--We--","start":3011.732,"stop":3011.949,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--argument--","start":3011.949,"stop":3012.909,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--Right, we think all--","start":3012.909,"stop":3013.109,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--you can take.","start":3013.109,"stop":3013.276,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--we think all three arguments are strong.","start":3013.276,"stop":3014.853,"duration":1.58},{"text":"I don't think... one isn't necessarily stronger than the other.","start":3014.853,"stop":3017.952,"duration":3.1},{"text":"And... but... and this Court... but if the Court... I mean, the Court certainly, at a minimum, can look at the statutes under California law, and can certainly conclude from the statutes that if a... if some... if an inmate doesn't sign the papers, he stays in prison until his sentence basically terminates.","start":3017.952,"stop":3035.092,"duration":17.14},{"text":"And then... and then, at that point, when he's released, this... another provision, Section 3060.5, kicks in, and his parole... his parole is revoked.","start":3035.092,"stop":3044.5,"duration":9.41},{"text":"And he eventually will... he ultimately will serve his whole term of parole in prison, so that the Court can see by the statutes that it is, effectively, a choice, statutorily, that he... someone who does not want to be on parole does not have... does not have to sign the condition, and will never go on parole.","start":3044.5,"stop":3059.867,"duration":15.37}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Long seemed to have... tell us something different about that.","start":3059.867,"stop":3064.149,"duration":4.28},{"text":"It's... they had... they must go out.","start":3064.149,"stop":3066.009,"duration":1.86},{"text":"He seemed to say they didn't have the choice of staying in.","start":3066.009,"stop":3069.941,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it's fairly clear, Your Honor, under... if you look at the appendix to the Petitioner's brief, if you... if you look at a combination of Section 3067(b), and then... which--","start":3069.941,"stop":3086.17,"duration":16.23}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I think he said he was unaware of anybody who was dragged out kicking and screaming, if I--","start":3086.17,"stop":3090.102,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--Right.","start":3090.102,"stop":3090.452,"duration":0.35},{"text":"And then--","start":3090.452,"stop":3090.535,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--recall his answer--","start":3090.535,"stop":3090.735,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--and if you look at--","start":3090.735,"stop":3090.868,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--on that.","start":3090.868,"stop":3091.002,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--3067(b), and then you also look at... 3067(a) and (b), and then you look at Section 3060.5, which provides for revocation if the... if the inmate is... or the parolee is unwilling to--","start":3091.002,"stop":3104.142,"duration":13.14}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But it really--","start":3104.142,"stop":3104.525,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--sign the--","start":3104.525,"stop":3105.236,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--it really isn't.","start":3105.236,"stop":3106.002,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--agreement.","start":3106.002,"stop":3106.102,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"It's... this is not like you sign an agreement and you're... you can do it or you can not do it.","start":3106.102,"stop":3110.612,"duration":4.51},{"text":"I mean, this is a real Hobson's choice, isn't it?","start":3110.612,"stop":3113.8,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you know, again, if you think that--","start":3113.8,"stop":3116.404,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"You can't--","start":3116.404,"stop":3116.621,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--there--","start":3116.621,"stop":3117.021,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--negotiate, \"I don't\"--","start":3117.021,"stop":3117.665,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--There--","start":3117.665,"stop":3117.765,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--\"# want this part\".","start":3117.765,"stop":3117.998,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--There undoubtedly are adverse consequences to not signing the agreement.","start":3117.998,"stop":3122.13,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Could you--","start":3122.13,"stop":3122.875,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"But--","start":3122.875,"stop":3123.109,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--waive your... could you waive--","start":3123.109,"stop":3124.219,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--But--","start":3124.219,"stop":3124.386,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--your eighth amendment rights?","start":3124.386,"stop":3125.153,"duration":0.77},{"text":"You know, if your parole's revoked, you're going to go back into a very cruel and unusual prison, not the one you left.","start":3125.153,"stop":3131.856,"duration":6.7}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I mean, I think... I think the test would be whether it's... whether it's reasonably the consent... what they're asking you to agree to is reasonably related to the purposes of punishment.","start":3131.856,"stop":3141.858,"duration":10},{"text":"And, in this case, the... you know, the supervision of the parolee, rehabilitation, protection of public safety.","start":3141.858,"stop":3147.901,"duration":6.04},{"text":"And so, we think the consent argument works very well here.","start":3147.901,"stop":3150.355,"duration":2.45},{"text":"But, if I could, I'd like to also address our arguments under the totality of the circumstances and special needs.","start":3150.355,"stop":3158.158,"duration":7.8},{"text":"Faced with a serious recidivism problem, California has made the reasonable judgment that subjecting parolees to suspicionless searches is necessary to protect public safety and to promote rehabilitation.","start":3158.158,"stop":3168.161,"duration":10}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What if it's the case--","start":3168.161,"stop":3168.444,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"But--","start":3168.444,"stop":3168.911,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--that this program would allow some searches that are... that violate the fourth amendment, but that this particular search would not?","start":3168.911,"stop":3178.58,"duration":9.67},{"text":"How closely can we focus just on what happened here, or do we have to consider all the... all the types of searches and the circumstances of searches that the California program might permit?","start":3178.58,"stop":3190.582,"duration":12}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I... no, I mean, I think typically this Court applies a very, sort of, narrowly tailored approach to fourth amendment questions, and focuses narrowly on the context in which the search was conducted.","start":3190.582,"stop":3202.944,"duration":12.36},{"text":"In this case, for example, you wouldn't... you wouldn't have to reach the question of whether a search of a home was constitutional.","start":3202.944,"stop":3209.982,"duration":7.04},{"text":"This... I mean, the question here is whether a search of the Petitioner on a public street was constitutional.","start":3209.982,"stop":3214.775,"duration":4.79},{"text":"And the Court does typically limit its fourth amendment cases to the facts presented.","start":3214.775,"stop":3218.563,"duration":3.79},{"text":"So... but, at the same time, in analyzing that, I think you do have to consider what the fourth amendment standard is.","start":3218.563,"stop":3226.027,"duration":7.46},{"text":"And we believe the fourth amendment does impose... the fourth amendment itself imposes restrictions on the discretion of police officers and parole officers that are meaningful, that... as the Reyes Court said, there are restrictions on the timing, the frequency, the duration, and the oppressiveness of the search.","start":3226.027,"stop":3244,"duration":17.97},{"text":"So, police officers and parole officers are on notice that courts will review suspicionless searches very carefully.","start":3244,"stop":3250.47,"duration":6.47},{"text":"They're on notice that there are limits to what they can do.","start":3250.47,"stop":3252.824,"duration":2.35},{"text":"And they're--","start":3252.824,"stop":3254.252,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"But following--","start":3254.252,"stop":3254.802,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--on notice that--","start":3254.802,"stop":3255.179,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--up on Justice--","start":3255.179,"stop":3255.896,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--if a search is--","start":3255.896,"stop":3256.112,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--Alito's thought, supposing there were no restrictions whatsoever, but this particular search didn't seem very offensive.","start":3256.112,"stop":3262.066,"duration":5.95},{"text":"Would you still defend it?","start":3262.066,"stop":3263.743,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--If there were no... no, we... no, we think there are... the fourth amendment imposes restrictions... time, place, and manner restrictions... on the suspicionless searches.","start":3263.743,"stop":3274.579,"duration":10.84}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3274.579,"stop":3275.162,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"And so, that--","start":3275.162,"stop":3276.756,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"He's asking you, I think, Justice Alito's question,","start":3276.756,"stop":3280.788,"duration":4.03},{"text":"\"Do we have to get into that? \"","start":3280.788,"stop":3283.393,"duration":2.61},{"text":"So long as this one's okay, why do... why do we have to get into whether there might be some other ones that aren't okay?","start":3283.393,"stop":3290.463,"duration":7.07}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--I... that's correct.","start":3290.463,"stop":3292.552,"duration":2.09},{"text":"I don't... I mean, I--","start":3292.552,"stop":3292.952,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"And it--","start":3292.952,"stop":3293.396,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think you just--","start":3293.396,"stop":3294.262,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--it was assumed California--","start":3294.262,"stop":3295.24,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--Right.","start":3295.24,"stop":3295.44,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--didn't say if they had protection against harassment and so forth.","start":3295.44,"stop":3298.938,"duration":3.5},{"text":"Suppose they just said,","start":3298.938,"stop":3299.788,"duration":0.85},{"text":"\"Cart blanche, you can search any parolee at any time, any place. \"","start":3299.788,"stop":3303.554,"duration":3.77},{"text":"And then you'd ask whether this search was reasonable.","start":3303.554,"stop":3305.831,"duration":2.28},{"text":"Would--","start":3305.831,"stop":3306.031,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":3306.031,"stop":3306.181,"duration":0.15},{"text":"And--","start":3306.181,"stop":3306.358,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--that be--","start":3306.358,"stop":3306.825,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think, in determining that, you would... in determining it and looking at the facts of this case, you would... you would apply a fourth amendment standard to determine whether this search was objectively reasonable.","start":3306.825,"stop":3315.639,"duration":8.81},{"text":"And you would look at factors like the time, place, frequency, and manner to determine whether a search was, in fact, reasonable--","start":3315.639,"stop":3321.848,"duration":6.21}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--So, it would uphold this.","start":3321.848,"stop":3323.014,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--and objective--","start":3323.014,"stop":3323.192,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"There's--","start":3323.192,"stop":3323.342,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--objective--","start":3323.342,"stop":3323.508,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"John Paul Stevens","textObjs":[{"text":"--no matter now unreasonable the California statute might be in other applications.","start":3323.508,"stop":3328.123,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's correct.","start":3328.123,"stop":3329.884,"duration":1.76},{"text":"And it's to see whether it's objective... whether the search in this case was objectively related to the purposes of supervision, to protect public safety, and to promote rehabilitation.","start":3329.884,"stop":3338.458,"duration":8.57},{"text":"That, we think, is the test under the fourth amendment.","start":3338.458,"stop":3340.719,"duration":2.26},{"text":"And while Petitioner points out that there are a hundred cases out there where the standard, you know, hasn't been used to throw out a search, at the same time, he hasn't pointed to any cases where a prosecution has been based on an abusive search that this standard has been too toothless to throw out.","start":3340.719,"stop":3355.421,"duration":14.7},{"text":"And we think that's significant, given that this type of condition has been in place for over 20 years for probationers, since the Bravo decision in 1987.","start":3355.421,"stop":3363.418,"duration":8},{"text":"And the parole condition has been in place since 1996, when the Legislature authorized this and made a considered decision to switch from a reasonable suspicion standard to a suspicionless standard for parolees.","start":3363.418,"stop":3373.654,"duration":10.24}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"The Government... is the Government of the United States somewhat behind the State of California?","start":3373.654,"stop":3380.374,"duration":6.72},{"text":"It's not efficient in... as efficient as California in supervising its parolees?","start":3380.374,"stop":3384.84,"duration":4.47},{"text":"Because you don't have this rule.","start":3384.84,"stop":3386.761,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"We don't have this program.","start":3386.761,"stop":3388.938,"duration":2.18},{"text":"There are... I mean, District Courts have the authority to impose a suspicionless search condition.","start":3388.938,"stop":3394.742,"duration":5.8},{"text":"And some have.","start":3394.742,"stop":3396.086,"duration":1.34},{"text":"I think the important thing to keep in mind here is that this is a... the Court has traditionally given a lot of deference to States in dealing with convicted felons in their criminal justice system, in making sentencing determinations, reasonable sentencing determinations, as this Court emphasized in the Ewing decision.","start":3396.086,"stop":3415.069,"duration":18.98},{"text":"And so, California clearly has a big problem on their hands.","start":3415.069,"stop":3419.518,"duration":4.45},{"text":"The recidivism rates are demonstrated, they're in the record.","start":3419.518,"stop":3422.289,"duration":2.77},{"text":"The... California was responding to those high recidivism rates.","start":3422.289,"stop":3425.655,"duration":3.37},{"text":"They were also responding to some high profile crimes involving parolees.","start":3425.655,"stop":3429.853,"duration":4.2},{"text":"And the... and, on top of that, we do have a brief that's submitted by 21 States who say that they do need this authority to effectively supervise parolees.","start":3429.853,"stop":3438.601,"duration":8.75}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Has--","start":3438.601,"stop":3438.701,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"But--","start":3438.701,"stop":3438.934,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--the recidivism rate gone down in the years since the Reyes decision, since this is suspicionless search, as opposed to reasonable suspicion?","start":3438.934,"stop":3449.17,"duration":10.24}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I... I mean, I'm not sure if the studies have been... statistics have been, sort of, documented up to this... to this date, but I think it's fair to say that it would be difficult to draw conclusions from those statistics, because, of course, this gives... this provision gives the California parole and police officers more authority to conduct searches; and so, there's... to the extent it's increasing the detection of crime, and so more people are actually being, you know, put back in prison on a parole violation or a criminal violation, it wouldn't necessarily mean that it's... this isn't, you know, being successful in reducing recidivism, because there's--","start":3449.17,"stop":3483.449,"duration":34.28}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do--","start":3483.449,"stop":3483.632,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"--I mean, there's that side to it, too.","start":3483.632,"stop":3485.293,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"David H. Souter","textObjs":[{"text":"--Even apart from the... what... the lack of evidence for any change since the Reyes decision, do we have any empirical evidence, perhaps involving a control group, about the likelihood of the... this liberal search policy in reducing recidivism?","start":3485.293,"stop":3506.797,"duration":21.5}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"May I answer the question, Your Honor?","start":3506.797,"stop":3508.307,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Go ahead.","start":3508.307,"stop":3508.591,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan L. Marcus","textObjs":[{"text":"I think, you know, traditionally this Court has been very deferential to State decisions on... you know, on efficacy, on whether a particular program is going to be efficacious... I mean, cases like Martinez Fuerte and the Sitz decision involving checkpoints for drunk driving... in a court.","start":3508.591,"stop":3524.008,"duration":15.42},{"text":"Even with, you know, very strong, you know, low efficacy rates... in, you know, a program that's showing very low efficacy rates, the Court said that these are judgment that... judgments that the States need to make, and they ought to be given a lot of deference, even if, you know, their... you know, the numbers, you know, of... don't show, by clear and convincing proof, that the problem isn't being ameliorated.","start":3524.008,"stop":3546.19,"duration":22.18}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Marcus.","start":3546.19,"stop":3547.701,"duration":1.51},{"text":"Mr. Long, you have 2 minutes remaining.","start":3547.701,"stop":3550.472,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In answer to Justice Alito's question, this search is unconstitutional, because the officer was completely at liberty... he had complete discretion to decide whether to search.","start":3550.472,"stop":3563.751,"duration":13.28},{"text":"And it would not be acceptable if California said,","start":3563.751,"stop":3567.1,"duration":3.35},{"text":"\"You can search anybody on the street. \"","start":3567.1,"stop":3568.861,"duration":1.76},{"text":"if the answer was,","start":3568.861,"stop":3570.205,"duration":1.34},{"text":"\"Well, it wasn't a particularly invasive search. \"","start":3570.205,"stop":3572.31,"duration":2.11},{"text":"Granted, parolees have far less fourth amendment rights than others, but this is so much the core of the fourth amendment.","start":3572.31,"stop":3581.385,"duration":9.08},{"text":"This is what the framers wrote the fourth amendment to stop, these general warrants and writs of assistance.","start":3581.385,"stop":3586.167,"duration":4.78},{"text":"One--","start":3586.167,"stop":3586.45,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But we--","start":3586.45,"stop":3586.667,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--consent--","start":3586.667,"stop":3587.111,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--we normally don't look into the mind of the officer to decide whether his action was okay or not.","start":3587.111,"stop":3592.887,"duration":5.78}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Long, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, and we're not asking you to look into the mind of the officer.","start":3592.887,"stop":3597.185,"duration":4.3},{"text":"It's... California's system, it's quite clear... they admitted it here... leaves it up to... the officer can have any reason for doing the search.","start":3597.185,"stop":3604.567,"duration":7.38},{"text":"It's arbitrary, in the sense this Court would use, but not California.","start":3604.567,"stop":3608.172,"duration":3.61},{"text":"On consent, very quickly, footnote 16 of our reply brief, the California Supreme Court has said repeatedly that... including very recently, since this Section 3067... that parole is not a matter of consent; it is imposed on you.","start":3608.172,"stop":3625.144,"duration":16.97},{"text":"This is a question of State law.","start":3625.144,"stop":3626.988,"duration":1.84},{"text":"Perhaps this Court would read the State law differently.","start":3626.988,"stop":3629.676,"duration":2.69},{"text":"But, as the Court said in Griffin, the State Supreme Court is the last word on the questions of State law.","start":3629.676,"stop":3636.23,"duration":6.55},{"text":"As to abuses, there are a number.","start":3636.23,"stop":3639.512,"duration":3.28},{"text":"One that I'll just mention, the California Supreme Court has held that it's perfectly okay... if the officer knows somebody in the house is on parole or probation, they can use that as a lever to go in and search to try to find evidence about somebody else who's in the house.","start":3639.512,"stop":3654.213,"duration":14.7},{"text":"That is permissible under the California standard.","start":3654.213,"stop":3657.317,"duration":3.1},{"text":"But the bottom line here is that this type of search regime is at the core of the prohibition of the fourth amendment.","start":3657.317,"stop":3667.143,"duration":9.83},{"text":"It's what the framers wrote the fourth amendment to prohibit.","start":3667.143,"stop":3670.692,"duration":3.55},{"text":"So, if parolees have any fourth amendment rights, other than, you know, an essentially useless arbitrary and capricious standard that's never going to work, the fourth amendment has to prohibit this search.","start":3670.692,"stop":3683.865,"duration":13.17},{"text":"There are many other things the States can do.","start":3683.865,"stop":3686.22,"duration":2.36},{"text":"They have many options.","start":3686.22,"stop":3687.564,"duration":1.34},{"text":"This is at the endpoint on the spectrum.","start":3687.564,"stop":3689.824,"duration":2.26},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3689.824,"stop":3690.602,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Long. The case is submitted.","start":3690.602,"stop":3694.602,"duration":4}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Roberts Court","arguedOn":"Feb 22, 2006","petitioner":"Donald Curtis Samson","respondent":"California","docket":"04-9728","citation":"547 US 843 (2006)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/547/843","lowerCourt":"State appellate court","grantedOn":"Sep 27, 2005","decidedOn":"Jun 19, 2006"}